# DSP Architecture Refactor: Separating Spatial Localization from Distance Modeling

## Problem Analysis: Why "Distance → HRTF & Air Absorption" is Wrong

### The Conceptual Error
The current grouping treats HRTF as a *distance* cue, but this is a category error. Here's the breakdown:

| Cue Type | Mechanism | What It Encodes |
|---|---|---|
| **HRTF (spectral shaping)** | Pinna/concha reflections → direction-dependent IIR filtering | **Azimuth + Elevation** (directional localization) |
| **ITD** (Interaural Time Difference) | Arrival time offset between ears | **Azimuth** (lateral angle, ±90°) |
| **ILD** (Interaural Level Difference) | Head-shadow amplitude asymmetry | **Azimuth** (especially >1.5 kHz) |
| **Air absorption** | HF attenuation ∝ distance (0.5–2 dB/100m above 8 kHz) | **Distance** — weakly |
| **Inverse-square rolloff** | Amplitude ∝ 1/r² | **Distance** — primary cue |
| **Direct-to-Reverb ratio (D/R)** | More reverb = more perceived distance | **Distance** — perceptually dominant |
| **Initial Time Delay Gap (ITDG)** | Gap between direct sound and first reflection | **Distance** (+ room size) |

**HRTF encodes *direction*, not distance.** Grouping it under "Distance" is the DSP equivalent of labeling a compass as a speedometer — both are spatial instruments but encode completely orthogonal dimensions.

The current code comment on `HrtfModule` even says:
> "pinna cascade models pinna reflections that provide elevation + distance cues"

This is partially incorrect: pinna spectral cues primarily encode **elevation and front/back discrimination**. Distance perception from HRTF is a secondary, speculative inference — not a primary mechanism.

